KABUL (Reuters) - The New York Times said on Tuesday that a man it had described as a "Taliban leader" who had taken part in "secret peace talks" with the Afghan government was in fact an impostor.&lt;div class="feedflare"&gt;
&lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=cK05MQN5KKQ:fv7OBWjEkiI:yIl2AUoC8zA"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=cK05MQN5KKQ:fv7OBWjEkiI:F7zBnMyn0Lo"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=cK05MQN5KKQ:fv7OBWjEkiI:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=cK05MQN5KKQ:fv7OBWjEkiI:V_sGLiPBpWU"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=cK05MQN5KKQ:fv7OBWjEkiI:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
