LONDON (Reuters) - An estimated 33.3 million people worldwide have the HIV virus that causes AIDS, but the global health community is starting to slow down and even turn the epidemic around, a United Nations report said on Tuesday.&lt;div class="feedflare"&gt;
&lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=QontpSBgQkA:Bh73Qb-E-eE:yIl2AUoC8zA"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=QontpSBgQkA:Bh73Qb-E-eE:F7zBnMyn0Lo"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=QontpSBgQkA:Bh73Qb-E-eE:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=QontpSBgQkA:Bh73Qb-E-eE:V_sGLiPBpWU"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=QontpSBgQkA:Bh73Qb-E-eE:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
