&lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=CPGco-xp19k:KoVJziFFVps:yIl2AUoC8zA"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=CPGco-xp19k:KoVJziFFVps:F7zBnMyn0Lo"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=CPGco-xp19k:KoVJziFFVps:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=CPGco-xp19k:KoVJziFFVps:V_sGLiPBpWU"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=CPGco-xp19k:KoVJziFFVps:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/reuters/worldNews/~4/CPGco-xp19k" height="1" width="1"/&gt;

ROME (Reuters) - Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi narrowly survived a no-confidence vote on Tuesday that left his center-right government clinging to power and provoked the most violent protests seen in Rome for years.&lt;div class="feedflare"&gt;
&lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=Xe79f0_IFQ4:yupPf_FYG3c:yIl2AUoC8zA"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=Xe79f0_IFQ4:yupPf_FYG3c:F7zBnMyn0Lo"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=Xe79f0_IFQ4:yupPf_FYG3c:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.reuters.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?a=Xe79f0_IFQ4:yupPf_FYG3c:V_sGLiPBpWU"&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/reuters/worldNews?i=Xe79f0_IFQ4:yupPf_FYG3c:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
